    explanation: `Erratic breakthrough vaginal bleeding is seen in 30% of women who are recently started on combined oral contraceptive pills (COCPs). This percentage, however, decreases to only 10% after three months. This problem is more common with preparations that contain low-dose estrogen. If the history of erratic bleeding is less than three months, only reassurance is required as the condition resolves after three months of use in most women. Once the problem persists beyond three months, the next best step would be an increase in the dose of estrogen (e.g., to 50mcg). Progesterone-only methods such as Mirena (option C), Implanon (option E), or progesterone-only pills (POPs) (option A) are associated with erratic bleeding and spotting as a major adverse effect and are best avoided for a woman already complaining of erratic bleeding. Continuation of the same dose (option D), while the bleeding has persisted beyond three months, is incorrect as the issue is not likely to resolve on its own.`,
