    topic: "Obstetrics & Gynaecology",
    subtopic: "Postpartum contraception - Lactational amenorrhea",
    stem: `A 25-year-old woman presented for your advice regarding the choice of oral contraceptive pills after the delivery of her male baby two weeks ago. She used combined oral contraceptive pills before her last pregnancy. She is a non-smoker and breastfeeds her baby on demand. Which one of the following is the best choice in this situation?`,
    options: [
      { label: "A", text: `Restarting combined oral contraceptive pills.` },
      { label: "B", text: `Start progesterone-only pills` },
      { label: "C", text: `No contraception needed.` },
      { label: "D", text: `Advise condoms.` },
      { label: "E", text: `Refer to a gynecologist.` },
    ],
    correctAnswer: "C",
    explanation: `Option C is correct. Elevated prolactin levels and a reduction in gonadotropin-releasing hormone from the hypothalamus during lactation suppress ovulation. This results in a reduction in the luteinizing hormone (LH) release and inhibition of follicular maturation. Lactational amenorrhea (LAM) is an excellent method of contraception, provided that all the following criteria are met: the woman remains amenorrheic, less than six months since giving birth, and the baby is fully breastfed (or breastfed with very infrequent supplements). This woman is regularly breastfeeding her baby on demand; therefore, she probably does not need further contraception at least while breastfeeding in the first 6 months, but in reality, there is a slight risk of pregnancy (about 2%) if menstruation resumes.`,
