    correctAnswer: "B",
    explanation: `The rhythm method (calendar calculation) is a natural family planning method based on the timing of ovulation. For the rhythm method, the fertile window is calculated as follows: subtract 18 from the shortest cycle length to determine the first fertile day, and subtract 11 from the longest cycle length to determine the last fertile day. In this case, the shortest cycle is 26 days and the longest is 29 days. First fertile day = 26 - 18 = day 8. However, to account for sperm survival (which can be up to 5 days), the calculation is adjusted: First fertile day = 26 - 18 - 5 = day 6 (approximately). Last fertile day = 29 - 11 = day 18. However, accounting for ovum survival (approximately 12-24 hours), this is extended slightly: Last fertile day = 29 - 11 + 1 = day 19 (approximately). Therefore, the couple should abstain from day 6 to day 17 (or conservatively, day 6 to day 19 to be safer). The most commonly cited recommendation is from day 6 to day 17.`,
