    stem: `A 29-year-old woman presents to your practice with complaints of annoying pain and cramping with her periods, as well as a slight increase in her menstrual flow. She has had this problem since she started menstruating, and investigations revealed no apparent cause for the presentation. Recently, she was advised to take combined oral contraceptives (COCs) for both contraception and treatment of her dysmenorrhea and was started on microgynon 30 mcg. Her dysmenorrhea, however, persists. Which one of the following would be the next best step in management?`,
