    explanation: `The Royal Australian and New Zealand College of Obstetricians and Gynaecologists recommends that all infants of HCV-positive mothers should be screened at 12-18 months of age to determine whether they have been infected. This delay allows full clearance of maternal antibodies in the infant and avoids confusing results. Screening should be performed by antibody and, if positive, HCV RNA by PCR. Since this child is only 10 months old, the next best step would be to wait until she reaches 18 months to let the circulating antibodies clear. If the antibody titer remains positive beyond this time, HCV RNA serology would be the next step. Positive HCV RNA serology indicates the presence of hepatitis C virus and infection of the infant, warranting specialist referral.`,
