    explanation: `During pregnancy, the size of the thyroid gland increases by 15%, mostly due to increased vasculature. Estrogen causes the liver to produce more thyroid-binding globulin (TBG). This results in increased total T3 and T4 levels; however, free T3 and T4 remain unchanged. Increased glomerular infiltration rate (GFR) leads to more renal excretion of iodine. Pre-existing maternal hypothyroidism can lead to neuropsychological deficits in the baby; therefore, the thyroxin requirement should be precisely adjusted during pregnancy. Pregnancy is associated with an increase in demand for thyroxin by 25 to 30%, requiring a 30% increase in thyroxin dose as soon as the pregnancy is diagnosed. This is best achieved by taking 2 additional doses of thyroxin per week on confirmation of pregnancy. (In most cases increasing from 7 to 9 doses per week) TSH and free T4 should be rechecked after 4 weeks and monitored every 4-6 weeks in the first half of pregnancy and at least once between 26 and 32 weeks. The values should be maintained within the trimester-specific range. After delivery, the thyroxin dose can be reduced to the pre-pregnancy dose. Breastfeeding mothers do not need extra doses of thyroxin. Option E is incorrect because thyroxin requirement does increase in pregnancy and maintenance dose must be increased.`,
