    correctAnswer: "C",
    explanation: `In this scenario, secondary postpartum hemorrhage (between 24 hours and 12 weeks postpartum) that is bright red and fever suggests retained products of conception (RPOC). A scant amount of lochia in the first few days after delivery suggests that the placental site may not have undergone involution, probably due to RPOC. Usually, retained products undergo necrosis with fibrin deposition and may eventually form a placental polyp. As the scar of the polyp detaches from the myometrium, brisk hemorrhage may occur. The necrotic products may also become infected and cause uterine infection, presented by fever, lower abdominal pain, and uterine tenderness. Endometritis can cause fever, offensive-odor lochia, and abdominal pain/tenderness but occurs within the first 5 days postpartum with peak incidence between days 2-3; bright red bleeding makes endometritis less likely. Genital lacerations are another cause of postpartum fever with peak incidence between days 4-5; however, wound infection does not affect the normal course of lochia and does not have heavy bright red bleeding as an expected feature. A cervical tear tends to present with primary rather than secondary postpartum hemorrhage and does not affect lochia. Uterine rupture is very unlikely to occur after 24 hours of delivery.`,
