    id: "og-amedex-0120",
    topic: "Obstetrics & Gynaecology",
    subtopic: "Gestational Thrombocytopenia",
    stem: `A 25-year-old woman presents at 20 weeks gestation for an antenatal check-up. Laboratory studies reveal a platelet count of 90,000/mm³ with no other abnormalities in test results. She has no symptoms and physical examination is unremarkable. Which one of the following could be the most likely diagnosis?`,
    options: [
      { label: "A", text: `Idiopathic thrombocytopenia.` },
      { label: "B", text: `Immune thrombocytopenia.` },
      { label: "C", text: `Gestational thrombocytopenia.` },
      { label: "D", text: `Disseminated intravascular coagulation (DIC).` },
      { label: "E", text: `Preeclampsia.` },
    ],
    correctAnswer: "C",
    explanation: `Thrombocytopenia is the second most common hematological finding during pregnancy after anemia. Gestational thrombocytopenia (incidental thrombocytopenia) occurs in approximately eight percent of all pregnancies and accounts for more than 70% of cases with thrombocytopenia in pregnancy. Although the pathophysiology of gestational thrombocytopenia is unknown, it is thought to be related to hemodilution, increased platelet consumption, and increased platelet aggregation (as a result of increased levels of thromboxane A2). Gestational thrombocytopenia is defined by: (1) mild and asymptomatic thrombocytopenia, (2) no past history of thrombocytopenia (except possibly during a previous pregnancy), (3) occurrence during late gestation (from the mid-second trimester to the third trimester), (4) no association with fetal thrombocytopenia, and (5) spontaneous resolution after delivery. This woman has isolated and asymptomatic mild thrombocytopenia at 20 weeks gestation, consistent with either gestational thrombocytopenia or ITP. Given the high prevalence of gestational thrombocytopenia, this could be the most likely diagnosis. Immune thrombocytopenia and idiopathic thrombocytopenia are two names for one condition characterized by isolated thrombocytopenia of autoimmune origin that can present similar to gestational thrombocytopenia; however, gestational thrombocytopenia is much more common during pregnancy and more likely to be the underlying cause of this woman's presentation. DIC is a serious life-threatening condition presenting with low-platelet count, intravascular coagulation, and thrombus formation potentially in every organ system. An asymptomatic isolated thrombocytopenia is not a picture consistent with DIC. Although thrombocytopenia is a common feature of pregnancy-related hypertensive disorders such as pre-eclampsia or HELLP syndrome, with pre-eclampsia, other manifestations of clinical or laboratory findings would be expected (e.g., proteinuria, hypertension, elevated liver enzymes, headache, abdominal pain, etc.). An isolated mild thrombocytopenia in a completely asymptomatic pregnant woman is unlikely to have been caused by pre-eclampsia.`,
