    explanation: `In second-trimester vaginal bleeding, the priority is haemodynamic stability of the mother, followed by prompt assessment of the cause of bleeding. A transvaginal ultrasound scan is the cornerstone in the evaluation of vaginal bleeding in the second trimester. The main purpose of ultrasonography is to find an underlying cause of the bleeding. Reasons to perform an ultrasound include: determining whether the placenta covers the cervical os (placenta previa), whether there is evidence of decidual haemorrhage causing placental separation (abruption), whether the cervix shows signs of cervical insufficiency, and whether there is a cervical polyp. Common causes of vaginal bleeding in the second and third trimesters include bloody shows associated with cervical insufficiency or labour, placenta previa, placental abruption, uterine rupture, and vasa previa.`,
