    correctAnswer: "A",
    explanation: `Normal pregnancy is associated with profound changes in almost every organ system to accommodate the demands of the fetoplacental unit. Serum albumin, transaminases (AST and ALT), and total bilirubin are decreased compared to non-pregnant states due to the expansion of extracellular volume. The only exception is serum alkaline phosphatase (ALP), which is elevated due to ALP of placental origin. During pregnancy, total serum calcium, phosphate, and magnesium are low due to the expanded intravascular space. The reduced albumin concentration also affects calcium concentrations. The reasons for hypocalcemia during pregnancy are (1) plasma expansion that, through dilutional effect, causes decreased plasma calcium and albumin concentration and (2) increased urinary excretion of calcium due to increased GFR. The serum parathyroid hormone concentration is usually 50% lower in pregnancy despite the decreased serum calcium concentration. Thyroid-stimulating hormone (TSH) normally decreases during the first trimester of pregnancy, during which human chorionic gonadotropin (hCG) maximally cross-stimulates the TSH receptor.`,
