    correctAnswer: "B",
    explanation: `Placental abruption occurs when a normally implanted placenta (not in the lower uterine segment) separates from the uterine wall before delivery of the fetus. Separation can be partial or complete. The condition is associated with vaginal bleeding of varying extent and a tense, tender uterus (option A). Commonly, the bleeding is overt and external (80% of cases); however, on occasions, the bleeding may be concealed with blood accumulating between the uterine wall and the placenta. This can lead to uterine haematoma and an increased size of the fundal height. Concealed bleeding, if severe, can result in haemorrhagic shock not justified by the amount of external bleeding (option C). Depending on the gestational age, the fetal head can be felt in the pelvic brim or above it (option D). An already engaged head can lose its position if placental abruption occurs. Placental abruption is a serious condition capable of putting both the mother and the fetus in jeopardy. In utero, fetal demise (option E) is a major concern. There are several conditions associated with an increased risk of placental abruption, with hypertension being one, but placental abruption does not result in hypertension. Blood pressure elevation is not expected as a direct result of placental abruption (option B).`,
