    topic: "Obstetrics & Gynaecology",
    subtopic: "Preterm labor - fetal fibronectin testing",
    stem: `A 35-year-old woman presents with regular uterine contractions at 34 weeks gestation. A sterile speculum examination is performed, showing cervical dilation of 2 cm and intact membranes. Which one of the following investigations is the best negative predictor of imminent birth within the next seven days?`,
    options: [
      { label: "A", text: `Transvaginal ultrasound.` },
      { label: "B", text: `Mid-stream urine sample.` },
      { label: "C", text: `The absence of fetal fibronectin in cervical secretions.` },
      { label: "D", text: `The presence of fetal fibronectin in cervical secretions.` },
      { label: "E", text: `Irregular uterine contractions.` },
    ],
    correctAnswer: "C",
    explanation: `Preterm labor is defined as regular uterine contractions after 20 weeks but before 37 weeks gestation, associated with cervical shortening and effacement. Risk factors for preterm labor include infections, antepartum hemorrhage, uterine distension, and spontaneous rupture of membranes. Fetal fibronectin (fFN) is considered a 'trophoblast glue' that promotes cellular adhesion at uterine-placental and decidual-fetal membrane interfaces. It is released into cervicovaginal secretions when the extracellular matrix of the chorionic/decidual interface is disrupted; this is the rationale for the measurement of fFN as a predictor of preterm delivery. The absence of fFN in cervical secretions is the most useful negative predictor of imminent birth within the next seven days. This test is performed at the bedside using a commercial test kit according to the instructions which are provided by the kit. It is very expensive but useful. Candidates for the fibronectin test are pregnant women who meet the following criteria: intact fetal membranes, cervical dilation less than 3 cm, and gestational age of between 22+0d – 34+6d weeks. At 34 weeks gestation, with a cervical dilation of 2 cm and intact membrane fibronectin test is the best negative predictor, meaning that with a negative test, preterm labor within the next 7 days would be unlikely. In the presence of fFN (positive test), one cannot tell with certainty that preterm labor will follow. Other steps to take are obtaining vaginal swabs and midstream urine for evaluation of vaginal infection and colonization with group B streptococcus. Ultrasonography is performed to assess cervical length, placental position, and presentation before the fFN is performed. A sterile speculum examination should be considered to exclude rupture of membranes.`,
