    correctAnswer: "E",
    explanation: `For first-trimester Down syndrome screening, maternal serum free beta hCG (along with pregnancy-associated plasma protein A (PAPPA)) is measured, whereas total HCG is measured for second-trimester screening. Free beta hCG can be used instead of total hCG for second-trimester screening. The difference between the detection rates of free beta hCG and total hCG for Down syndrome remains controversial; however, recent studies showed that the application of free beta hCG is associated with a 4% increase in the detection of Down syndrome (not certain yet). Alpha-fetoprotein (option A), inhibin A (option B), and unconjugated estriol levels (option C) are used to screen for Down syndrome solely in the second trimester. Pregnancy-associated plasma protein A (PAPP-A) level (option D) is used as a screening method only during the first trimester.`,
