    topic: "Obstetrics & Gynaecology",
    subtopic: "Large-for-date uterus assessment",
    stem: `A 32-year-old female is 14 weeks pregnant and presents for antenatal follow-up. On examination, her fundal height is 18 cm. Which one of the following would be the next best step in managing this patient?`,
    options: [
      { label: "A", text: `Check serum beta hCG level.` },
      { label: "B", text: `Order an ultrasound scan.` },
      { label: "C", text: `Reassure that this is normal.` },
      { label: "D", text: `Refer to a gynecologist.` },
      { label: "E", text: `Review in four weeks.` },
    ],
    correctAnswer: "B",
    explanation: `A pregnant fundus is expected to be palpable above the pubis symphysis at 12 weeks gestation. At 20 weeks, it is expected to be felt at the level of the umbilicus. Between 12 and 20 weeks, the uterus stands in between. After 20 weeks, the fundal height in centimeters is equivalent to the number of weeks of pregnancy. A fundal height of 18cm is definitely large for a 14-week pregnant uterus. The most common cause of such discrepancy is dating errors; hence, the next best step would be performing an ultrasound scan for a more accurate estimation of the gestational age. Furthermore, ultrasonography can provide additional information about the conditions that might have led to a large-for-date uterus, such as polyhydramnios, multiple gestations, etc., if the case is not simply a dating error.`,
