    explanation: `Folic acid deficiency in the mother can result in fetal neural tube defects. Every woman should be started on folic acid at least one month before conception and continue during the first trimester. The current recommendation is to take 0.5 mg of folic acid daily or a multivitamin containing at least 0.4 mg of folic acid. Women should take ten times the minimal dose (4 to 5 mg per day) if there is a family or personal history of neural tube defects (NTDs) or a previous pregnancy with NTD, use of medications that affect folic acid absorption (e.g., antiepileptic medications), diabetes (type I/II), or mother's BMI>35 kg/m2. According to the NHMRC, the father's personal history of NTDs is another condition requiring a prescription for a high dose of folic acid. This woman has a previous history of a pregnancy associated with NTD; hence, she should be started on folic acid 4 to 5 mg per day from at least one month before conception and three months into the pregnancy.`,
