    explanation: `In this scenario, the 30-year-old woman at 30 weeks of gestation presents with decreased fetal movement, and the clinical exam reveals no detectable fetal heart sounds. This finding raises significant concern for possible fetal demise, which requires immediate confirmation and investigation. The next best step in management would be to schedule an ultrasound for fetal assessment to determine the fetal condition and guide further management. An ultrasound is the most appropriate next step to confirm the fetal condition. It allows for direct visualisation of the fetus, determination of fetal heart activity, and evaluating other important factors such as amniotic fluid volume, placental position, and fetal development. Given the absence of fetal heart sounds an ultrasound will help confirm whether there has been a fetal death or if there are other concerns, like oligohydramnios (low amniotic fluid) or other placental issues, which could explain the decreased movement. (Option A) An NST assesses fetal heart rate variability in response to fetal movements. However, the absence of fetal heart sounds on examination suggests the fetus may already be dead, making the NST ineffective in this case. An ultrasound is the more appropriate next step to assess the fetus directly and confirm the presence or absence of heart activity. (Option C) Advising the patient to rest and return in one week is inappropriate. Given the concern for fetal demise, waiting a week would delay critical diagnosis and intervention. (Option D) Inducing labour immediately could be considered if fetal demise is confirmed via ultrasound. However, induction is not the next step if fetal death is not yet confirmed. First, an ultrasound is necessary to assess the fetal condition and confirm whether fetal demise has occurred. If confirmed, labor induction or other management options would be considered, based on the clinical situation and gestational age. (Option E) Administering corticosteroids to promote fetal lung maturation is appropriate in cases of preterm labour or when early delivery is anticipated, but it would be premature in the case of suspected fetal demise without confirming the fetal status first. Corticosteroids are generally not given in the absence of a viable fetus.`,
