    explanation: `The scenario describes vaginal bleeding in the second half of the pregnancy (antepartum haemorrhage), most likely caused by the previously diagnosed grade IV placenta previa. The usual history includes a first episode of vaginal bleeding occurring at home. Bleeding is not often heavy. More episodes of bleeding can follow. The priority in patients with antepartum haemorrhage is assessing the vital signs, estimating blood loss (clinically and using laboratory tests), determining the blood group, and cross-matching. Of note, even an asymptomatic, currently stable placenta previa can lead to massive bleeding at any time. This is even more likely with higher grades of placenta previa or if the first episode of bleeding occurred before 30 weeks gestation. The abdomen should be palpated for uterine tenderness, contraction, and fetal presentation. Abdominal ultrasonography is needed to confirm the diagnosis and collect additional information about the situation. Cardiotocography should assess fetal well-being, and corticosteroids should be administered (if indicated) to promote fetal lung maturity due to an increased risk of premature labour. Anti-D (RhoGAM) (option C) should be administered if indicated, but it is not a priority. No vaginal examination should be made before placenta previa is excluded by ultrasound examination because this can lead to torrential bleeding. Transvaginal ultrasonography (option A) is more accurate than transabdominal (option D) and is the first choice of investigation if indicated. The probe is entered into the vagina to an extent and at an angle that prevents the probe from reaching the cervical os and is safe to perform in experienced hands. If labour is indicated, a cesarean section is considered. Labour induction (option E) is generally contraindicated in placenta previa except for cases with low-grade placenta previa and no other contraindications to vaginal delivery.`,
