    explanation: `Maternal hypothyroidism is not a contraindication to tocolysis. It is treated with thyroxine and is not a contraindication to labor suppression. The contraindications to tocolysis in preterm labor include: gestation >34 weeks or <24 weeks; advanced labor (cervical dilation >4 cm); chorioamnionitis; in utero fetal death; abnormal CTG suggesting non-reassuring fetal status; lethal fetal anomalies; intrauterine fetal demise; suspected fetal compromise; significant antepartum hemorrhage (placental abruption/active vaginal bleeding); suspected intrauterine infections; maternal hypotension; hemorrhage with hemodynamic instability; pregnancy-induced hypertension/eclampsia/pre-eclampsia; placenta previa; placental insufficiency; intrauterine growth retardation; severe preeclampsia; and maternal allergy to tocolytic agents or contraindications due to comorbidities. Known or suspected fetal pulmonary maturity is not an absolute contraindication, as nonpulmonary morbidities may benefit from prolonged pregnancy.`,
