    correctAnswer: "B",
    explanation: `Marked rebound tenderness in the suprapubic region with only a little or absent guarding is the most common exam finding in patients with ectopic pregnancy (EP). The rebound tenderness is caused by the presence of blood in the peritoneal cavity. Board-like rigidity is evident when chemicals or purulent material irritate the peritoneal cavity, and therefore board-like rigidity is not an expected finding in EP. The pain caused by a tubal ectopic pregnancy is often felt in the lower abdomen and suprapubic region rather than the affected side. Patients with EP have cervical motion tenderness rather than tenderness of the pouch of Douglas. Pelvic inflammatory disease (PID) is another differential diagnosis for cervical motion tenderness. In patients with EP, adnexal tenderness or pelvic tenderness in general is much more common than pelvic mass on the exam. A mass, if present, is more likely to have been caused by blood collection from an ectopic pregnancy rather than the ectopic pregnancy itself. Shock and its presentations (e.g., tachycardia, hypotension) are present when the ectopic pregnancy has ruptured and caused internal hemorrhage.`,
