    correctAnswer: "A",
    explanation: `Less than 10% of women with gestational diabetes mellitus (GDM) remain hyperglycemic after delivery. The management of these women requires ongoing care from a diabetes or medical clinic in collaboration with their general practitioner. The following are recommendations for women with gestational diabetes after delivery: checking a random blood glucose level the day after delivery; 4-point blood glucose level (BGL) measurement on the day prior to discharge (fasting and two hours post meals for three meals); cease blood glucose monitoring if BGL is within normal range; if BGL is elevated (above 10 mmol/L) contact the medical registrar/diabetes educator – if BGLs are considerably elevated, after-hours contacts are justified; it is recommended that women who have had GDM visit their GP for a follow-up oral glucose (75 gr) tolerance test at 6-12 weeks postpartum, and every 1-2 years thereafter; lifestyle counseling; and a summary letter is provided to the woman's GP for follow-up care. This woman should have a random BGL the day after delivery, a 4-point BGL test the day before discharge, and an oral glucose tolerance test using 75g glucose between weeks 6 and 12 after delivery. Checking HbA1C and fasting lipids would be required if this patient is found to have type 2 diabetes mellitus.`,
