    id: "og-amedex-0185",
    topic: "Obstetrics & Gynaecology",
    subtopic: "Threatened Abortion",
    stem: `A 21-year-old woman, G1P0, comes to your clinic at 12 weeks of pregnancy. She has been complaining of mild vaginal bleeding for the past 12 hours, associated with bouts of mild cramping and lower abdominal pain. On vaginal examination, the cervical os is closed, and there is mild discharge containing blood clots. Ultrasonography confirms the presence of a live fetus with a normal heart rate. Which one of the following is the most likely diagnosis?`,
    options: [
      { label: "A", text: `Threatened abortion.` },
      { label: "B", text: `Inevitable abortion.` },
      { label: "C", text: `Incomplete abortion.` },
      { label: "D", text: `Missed abortion.` },
      { label: "E", text: `Complete abortion.` },
    ],
    correctAnswer: "A",
    explanation: `Uterine bleeding in the presence of a closed cervix and sonographic visualization of an intrauterine pregnancy with detectable fetal cardiac activity is diagnostic of threatened abortion. The term 'threatened' is used because abortion does not always follow uterine bleeding in early pregnancy, even after repeated episodes or large amounts of bleeding. In fact, in 90 to 96% of cases who present with vaginal bleeding in the presence of a closed os and a detectable fetal heart rate, the pregnancy continues. The more advanced the gestational age, the less likely the condition will end in miscarriage. In inevitable abortion, there is a dilated cervix as well as progressive uterine bleeding and painful uterine contractions. The gestational tissue can often be felt or seen through the cervical os, and the passage of this tissue typically occurs within a short time. In incomplete abortion, the membranes may have ruptured, and the conception products may have partly passed, but significant amounts of placental tissue are still left in the uterus. This is the most common presentation of an abortion in the late first and early second trimester. On examination, the cervical os is open, gestational tissue may be observed in the cervix, and the uterine size is smaller than expected for gestational age. The uterus is not well contracted. The amount of bleeding varies but can be severe enough to cause hypovolemic shock. Painful contractions are often present. Ultrasound reveals tissue in the uterus. A missed abortion refers to in utero death of the embryo or fetus before 20 weeks gestation. Women may notice that symptoms associated with early pregnancy (nausea, breast tenderness, etc.) have abated, and they do not 'feel pregnant' anymore. Vaginal bleeding may occur, and the cervix usually remains closed. Ultrasound reveals an intrauterine gestational sac with or without an embryonic/fetal pole but no embryonic/fetal cardiac activity. In complete abortion, a miscarriage occurs before week 12, and the entire contents of the uterus are expelled. If this has occurred, the uterus is small on physical examination and well contracted with an open or closed cervix. There is scant vaginal bleeding and only mild cramping. Ultrasound will reveal an empty uterus and no extra-uterine pregnancy.`,
