    subtopic: "Preterm Prelabor Rupture of Membranes (PPROM)",
    stem: `A 34-year-old woman from rural Victoria presents to the hospital at 37 weeks gestation after she noticed a sudden gush of clear vaginal fluid. There are no uterine contractions. Speculum examination shows pooling of liquor in the posterior fornix. After 12 hours, she develops fever, tachycardia, and chills. In addition to giving antibiotics, which of the following would be the next best step in management?`,
