    correctAnswer: "C",
    explanation: `Rupture of membranes (ROM) is often a sign of imminent labor if it happens at term or near term. Once labor does not start within 4 hours of ROM, it will be called pre-labor ROM (PROM). PROM before 37 weeks of gestation is termed pre-term (premature) PROM or PPROM. The classic clinical presentation of ROM is a sudden gush of clear or pale yellow fluid from the vagina. One of the dreaded complications of PROM is chorioamnionitis, which is associated with severe maternal and fetal complications. This woman is not in labor 12 hours after the ROM. Therefore, she has a diagnosis of PROM. She also has developed signs of infection, indicated by fever, tachycardia, and chills. Once chorioamnionitis develops, the induction of labor (IOL) should be considered as soon as possible. Vaginal examination (option A) should be avoided in PROM unless delivery is imminent. Continuation of the pregnancy (option B) carries a significant risk of maternal and fetal jeopardy. Corticosteroids (option D) are given up to 34 weeks of gestation. At 37 weeks, systemic corticosteroids will have no effect on fetal lung maturity. In the presence of chorioamnionitis, where immediate induction of labor is indicated, corticosteroids would be of no use even if the gestational age was under 34 weeks.`,
