    correctAnswer: "C",
    explanation: `This woman has a high-risk pregnancy due to a multiple pregnancy and a history of placental abruption in the previous pregnancy, each of which alone is significant enough to warrant extra care for the patient. Risks and care associated with and needed for each condition are as follows: Placental abruption: Pregnancy following a placental abruption (PA) must be considered a high-risk pregnancy, not only in terms of increased risk of recurrence but also due to excess risk of small for gestational age, preterm labour, and birth and pregnancy-induced hypertension (PIH), irrespective of recurrence of placental abruption. Therefore, all pregnancies following a pregnancy complicated by placental abruption should be offered close antenatal surveillance. A significant risk factor for PA is abruption in a previous pregnancy. It is estimated that a woman with an earlier PA has a 5-10% chance of recurrent PA in subsequent pregnancies. The risk increases to 19-25% with two or more PAs. It is recommended that once a woman has a PA, close surveillance be performed in the subsequent pregnancies starting from 2-3 weeks (up to 3 months) before the gestational age at the PA occurs. There are limited measures to prevent subsequent PAs from developing except for intervention in modifiable risk factors (e.g., hypertension, smoking, amphetamine, and cocaine). Multiple pregnancies: Multiple pregnancy is associated with several potential maternal and fetal complications. For this woman, several measures should be contemplated, starting with increasing the dose of folate and iron supplementation as the best initial step. Multifetal pregnancies are associated with an increased risk of iron and folate deficiencies. Iron deficiency anemia is associated with an increased risk of preterm delivery and low ferritin levels with prematurity. Folate deficiency may result in neural tube defects and anemia (megaloblastic). Ultrasonographic assessment is recommended to start at 12-13 weeks gestation, where it can demonstrate whether the twins are monochorionic or dichorionic. If initial ultrasonography reveals a dichorionic twin pregnancy, serial sonographies should be carried out at 20, 28, 32, and 36 weeks. For monochorionic twin pregnancies, the time of subsequent sonographies will be at 16,19,22,26,30,33 and 36 weeks. CTG should be performed weekly after 34 weeks. As mentioned above, CTG and serial sonography provide the best method for monitoring discordant growth and evaluating fetal well-being through CTG monitoring, biophysical profiles, and Doppler studies. Previously, it was suggested that patients such as this woman be admitted around the time the previous PA occurred. Still, currently, there is not enough evidence to support a policy of routine hospitalization for bed rest in multiple pregnancies. No reduction in the risk of preterm birth or perinatal death is evident, although there is a suggestion that fetal growth is improved. In women with just multi-fetal pregnancy and no other complications, this measure is not only not useful, but it may result in an increased risk of very preterm birth. Until further evidence is available, the policy cannot be recommended for routine clinical practice.`,
