    correctAnswer: "B",
    explanation: `The risk of transmission of herpes simplex virus to the neonate and neonatal infection significantly increases if a pregnant woman develops primary herpes simplex infection after 30 weeks gestation. Risk factors for intrapartum herpes simplex infection of the baby include: premature labor, premature rupture of membrane, primary herpes simplex infection near the time of delivery, and multiple lesions in the genital area. The management includes: checking for herpes simplex infection with PCR testing (cervical swab), prophylactic antiviral therapy of the mother from 36th week until delivery, and cesarean section delivery. For this pregnant woman, antiviral therapy should be started, and a cesarean section should be performed to minimize the risk of vertical transmission. Vaginal delivery is contraindicated. Acyclovir given to the neonate after delivery is not the primary management. Topical lignocaine and antibiotics are not appropriate treatments for herpes simplex infection.`,
