    correctAnswer: "A",
    explanation: `Cord prolapse presents with abnormalities in fetal heart rate patterns (bradycardia, variable decelerations, etc.). If these changes begin after the membranes rupture, either spontaneously or with amniotomy, cord prolapse should be strongly suspected. Umbilical cord prolapse is the abnormal position of the cord in front of the fetal presenting part, resulting in cord compression during labour and fetal hypoxemia. Once the diagnosis of the cord prolapse is confirmed on pelvic examination and the cord is still pulsating (indicating the fetus is still alive), the presenting part should be pushed up with the examiner's finger, followed by pushing the cord up as far as possible and maintaining the digital pressure. The mother should be placed in the knee-chest position with the examiner's hand in place and rushed to the operating room for emergency cesarean delivery. With the child being unstable and severely hypoxemic (reflected by variable decelerations on heart rate monitoring) there is no place for vaginal delivery and emergency cesarean section should be performed.`,
