    correctAnswer: "D",
    explanation: `Free serum T4 (free thyroxine) is NOT elevated in the third trimester of pregnancy. Normally, estrogen stimulates and progesterone inhibits prolactin secretion; despite this counteraction, prolactin levels (option A) slightly rise throughout pregnancy. Serum alkaline phosphatase (ALP) (option B) is increased in pregnancy due to placental ALP. Physiologically, the concentration of thyroid-stimulating hormone (TSH) decreases during the first trimester of pregnancy when there is maximal cross-stimulation of the TSH receptor by hCG. The TSH concentration returns to its pre-pregnancy level in the second trimester and rises slightly in the third trimester. However, most of the changes still occur within the normal non-pregnant range. Free serum T3 and T4 concentrations remain unchanged during pregnancy, but total concentrations, including free and protein-bound fractions, are significantly elevated due to increased circulating binding globulins. Iron binding capacity reflects the protein used for iron transport and transferrin. Transferrin is a globulin in the beta band on electrophoresis. Both transferrin and iron binding capacity (option C) are elevated in pregnancy to counteract decreased plasma iron during pregnancy. Cortisol levels (option E) can be elevated up to three times normal compared to non-pregnant individuals.`,
