    correctAnswer: "C",
    explanation: `The measles (rubeola) virus is a single-stranded RNA virus of the family Paramyxoviridae. Measles is highly infectious with respiratory airborne droplet transmission. It has an incubation period of 10-14 days. Initial presentation includes fever, malaise, cough, coryza, conjunctivitis, and Koplik's spots. Two to four days after initial symptoms, a maculopapular rash develops, typically starting on the face and upper neck and spreading to involve the whole body. The infectivity period starts two days before the rash onset and continues for four days after eruption. In pregnant women, measles is associated with increased risk of preterm labor, spontaneous abortion, fetal/neonatal loss, and maternal mortality. This woman has an established diagnosis of measles and is already at increased risk of complications. There is no active treatment except conservative management. However, since measles is a 'notifiable' disease, notification should be made as soon as possible as the most appropriate next step in management. Option A: MMR is a live attenuated vaccine that has no role in managing established measles and is contraindicated throughout pregnancy. Option B: Normal human immunoglobulin (NHIG) is used for prophylaxis in contacts of an index case with measles in whom the MMR vaccine is contraindicated, e.g., a pregnant woman. Option D: Checking antibody status in this patient with established measles is of no use and will not change the management plan. Option E: It is inappropriate to take no action while measles is a notifiable disease. All cases of measles should be reported.`,
