    correctAnswer: "D",
    explanation: `Cord prolapse should be suspected where there is an abnormal fetal heart rate pattern (bradycardia, variable decelerations, etc.), particularly if such changes begin soon after the rupture of the membranes, spontaneously or with amniotomy. The following are risk factors predisposing to cord prolapse: Fetal malpresentation (breech, transverse lie, etc.) – Although fetal malpresentation is a risk factor, cord prolapses occur with vertex presentation because of the relatively low incidence of non-cephalic presentation; Unengaged fetal presenting part; Prematurity – Probably due to the smaller size of the fetus to the amniotic fluid volume and the increased frequency of malpresentation among premature fetuses; Multi-fetus gestation – The risk of cord prolapse in a term twin pregnancy is confined to the second-born twin, in whom there is an increased probability of malpresentation; Premature rupture of membranes – Iatrogenic or spontaneous rupture of membranes can lead to cord prolapse because a forceful flow of amniotic fluid may carry the cord beyond the presenting part. The highest risk of this occurrence is with preterm premature rupture of membranes, polyhydramnios, or an unengaged fetal presenting part; Abnormal placentation; Multiparity – Cord prolapse in multiparous women may be due to the increased likelihood of rupture of membranes before engagement of the presenting part since engagement in multiparas often occurs after labor has begun and later than in nulliparas; Polyhydramnios, e.g. in gestational diabetes – Polyhydramnios is often associated with an abnormal lie or unengaged presenting part, as well as flow of amniotic fluid after membrane rupture; Long umbilical cord; Pelvic deformities; Uterine tumors and malformations; Congenital anomalies; Interventions that may predispose to cord prolapse include: Iatrogenic rupture of membranes, Application of an internal scalp electrode, Insertion of an intrauterine pressure catheter, Manual rotation of the fetal head, Amnioinfusion or amnoreduction, External cephalic version in patients with ruptured membranes, Application of forceps or vacuum. Anemia is not a predisposing factor to cord prolapse.`,
