    correctAnswer: "C",
    explanation: `CMV (a DNA virus) is the most common cause of intrauterine infection and the most common viral cause of birth defects. Primary infection of the mother is often asymptomatic but may present as flu-like symptoms. Up to 50% of pregnant women are CMV IgG seropositive. Vertical transmission from mother to fetus occurs mainly during the viremia of a primary infection, with a 50% chance of transplacental fetal infection with primary infection, regardless of gestational age, but less than 1% with reactivation of a latent infection. Since this woman is 16 weeks pregnant, amniocentesis for a definite diagnosis is the most appropriate option. Amniocentesis is performed in the window of 15-18 (up to 20) weeks. The definite diagnosis of fetal infection is by amniocentesis and PCR or the amniotic fluid for CMV. Positive results do not predict any degree of fetal damage. Interpretation of CMV IgM results in pregnancy requires specialist opinion.`,
