    id: "og-amedex-0222",
    topic: "Obstetrics & Gynaecology",
    subtopic: "Early Pregnancy Loss and Ectopic Pregnancy",
    stem: `A 26-year-old woman with menstrual cycles ranging from 4 to 6 weeks presents with vaginal bleeding following amenorrhea of 6 weeks duration, which is heavier than ever and not like her previous periods. A urine pregnancy test is positive. On vaginal examination, the cervical os is closed. An endovaginal ultrasound scan is performed that reveals an endometrial thickness of 12 mm and an empty uterus. Adenexa is clear, and there is no fluid in Douglas's pouch. There is a corpus luteum cyst in the left ovary. Which one of the following would be the most likely diagnosis?`,
    options: [
      { label: "A", text: `Ectopic pregnancy.` },
      { label: "B", text: `False positive pregnancy test result.` },
      { label: "C", text: `Complete abortion.` },
      { label: "D", text: `Incomplete abortion.` },
      { label: "E", text: `Complicated corpus luteum cyst.` },
    ],
    correctAnswer: "C",
    explanation: `A positive pregnancy test, while the uterus is empty on an ultrasound exam, can be due to either of the following: a false positive pregnancy test, complete abortion, ectopic pregnancy, or early normal pregnancy. An endometrial thickness of 12 mm on ultrasound makes a false positive pregnancy test result less likely. If the woman is not pregnant and is experiencing normal menstruation in the 6th week (as she often does, according to the history), the endometrial thickness would be expected to be 2-4 mm. Several studies have been conducted to see whether measuring endometrial thickness would help distinguish ectopic pregnancy, early normal pregnancy, and complete abortion, but no meaningful results have yet been obtained. In fact, endometrial thickness could be similar in all these conditions; therefore, the only condition this parameter excludes is a false negative result. Since this woman has a corpus luteal cyst on ultrasound, a false positive result would become even less likely as it indicates there has been a recent pregnancy. After ovulation, the remnant of the follicle turns into a temporary endocrine structure that produces progesterone (pro = in favor of + progesterone = pregnancy)—an essential hormone for egg implantation and maintaining the pregnancy until the placenta fully takes over this function by 10-12 weeks gestation. If pregnancy does not happen, the corpus luteum involutes and disappears; otherwise, it grows in size and persists. If the patient were not pregnant, the corpus luteum cyst would be expected to have resolved by the time she started her menstruation. Since it has persisted, it is more likely that pregnancy has occurred. With clear adnexa, almost 97% of EPs are excluded; however, since ultrasound is highly operator-dependent, ectopic pregnancy cannot be ruled out with certainty. It is noteworthy that in uncomplicated ectopic pregnancies, there is no fluid collection in the pouch of Douglas; therefore, an empty pouch does not exclude ectopic pregnancy. The closed OS excludes incomplete abortion because OS will not completely close unless all the products of pregnancy are expelled and uterine contractions have stopped. Since the US findings do not favor EP, of the options, complete abortion remains the most likely diagnosis. This does not mean that EP is ruled out whatsoever. In fact, what was seen as a corpus luteum cyst could be an ovarian EP that has been misinterpreted, but compared to complete abortion, that would be far less likely.`,
