    correctAnswer: "A",
    explanation: `This patient has signs and symptoms suggestive of round ligament pain. It is considered a normal finding during pregnancy and requires no intervention. Round ligament pain most frequently occurs during the second trimester of pregnancy when women report sharp unilateral or bilateral pain in the iliac fossa that may radiate to the groin. The pain is often sudden-onset, sharp, and spastic, lasting a few seconds. The pain is aggravated by standing, getting off chairs, sneezing, laughing, or rolling in bed. Sudden change of position is a well-known trigger. Rest and avoiding sudden changes in body position are the cornerstone of management. (Option B) Although appendicitis presents with pain in the right iliac fossa, the absence of tenderness makes this diagnosis less likely. (Option C) Ovarian torsion presents with acute-onset severe pain followed by signs and symptoms of peritoneal irritation, such as tenderness, rebound tenderness, guarding, etc. (Options D and E) Presentation of ectopic pregnancy and its complications (e.g., rupture) almost always occurs in the first trimester; furthermore, the absence of tenderness, rebound tenderness, and other localized findings make this diagnosis even less likely. NOTE—The question asks about the most likely diagnosis, not the next best step in management. Although round ligament strain comes top on the list, more serious conditions should be excluded first through appropriate examination and investigations.`,
