    explanation: `Clinical guidelines for antenatal care by the National Health and Medical Research Council of Australia recommend folic acid 0.5 mg daily 12 weeks before conception and during the first trimester. The dose of folic acid is increased to 5mg daily in the following situations: history of neural tube defects in previous pregnancies, the pregnant woman is diabetic, or the pregnant woman is on anticonvulsant medications. It is also recommended that the mother take 150 micrograms of iodine daily throughout the pregnancy to prevent iodine deficiency in the fetus. She has taken folic acid for the first trimester; therefore, it can safely be stopped. While evidence supports routine supplementation with folic acid and iodine in pregnancy, other vitamin and mineral supplements are not beneficial unless there is an identified deficiency. Vitamin A, B, and C supplements are not routinely used in pregnancy.`,
