    id: "og-amedex-0227",
    topic: "Obstetrics & Gynaecology",
    subtopic: "Fetal Heart Rate Monitoring in Labor",
    stem: `A 39-week pregnant woman is admitted to the Labor Unit due to the commencement of labor pain and contractions. The woman is placed in the left lateral decubitus position and started on supplemental oxygen and a face mask. An intravenous line is established, and isotonic fluids and Syntocinon (oxytocin) drip are started according to the protocol. A CTG is performed that shows a fetal heart rate of 140 which drops to 70 bpm and returns back to the baseline of 140 bpm in two minutes. Which one of the following is the most appropriate immediate management?`,
    options: [
      { label: "A", text: `Stop Syntocinon.` },
      { label: "B", text: `Fetal scalp blood sampling.` },
      { label: "C", text: `Immediate cesarean section.` },
      { label: "D", text: `Titrate and increase the dose of Syntocinon.` },
      { label: "E", text: `Continuous CTG monitoring.` },
    ],
    correctAnswer: "E",
    explanation: `The CTG pattern described shows a variable deceleration (sudden drop in fetal heart rate from baseline to 70 bpm and return to baseline within 2 minutes). Variable decelerations are typically benign and are caused by umbilical cord compression. They are common during labor and do not necessarily indicate fetal distress. The appropriate management for variable decelerations is continuous fetal heart rate monitoring to assess for any concerning features such as slow return to baseline, failure to return to baseline, or rising baseline. The presence of reassuring features (such as normal baseline rate, good variability, and presence of accelerations) suggests fetal well-being. In this case, the fetal heart rate returns promptly to baseline, which is reassuring. Therefore, continuous CTG monitoring is the most appropriate immediate management. The other options are not indicated at this point: stopping Syntocinon, fetal scalp blood sampling, or immediate cesarean section would only be considered if there were signs of fetal distress or other concerning features on the CTG.`,
