    explanation: `Karyotyping of fetal cells is the only definite method to exclude Down syndrome with almost 100% accuracy. For this reason, fetal cells should be obtained through either chorionic villus sampling (CVS), amniocentesis, or cordocentesis. Amniocentesis carries the least risk compared to cordocentesis (option E) and chorionic villus sampling (option A) and is the best advisable option for her. CVS is performed at 10-12 weeks gestation with a miscarriage risk of 0.7% (1 in 100-150). Amniocentesis is performed at 15-20 weeks gestation with a miscarriage risk of 0.5% (1 in 200). Cordocentesis is performed after 20 weeks with a miscarriage risk of 1-2% (1 in 50-100). The triple marker screen test (maternal serum alpha-fetoprotein, estradiol, and β-HCG) (option D) and ultrasonography for nuchal fold translucency (option B) are screening tests, never used as definitive methods of diagnosis. Amniocentesis also allows analysis of amniotic fluid for alpha-fetoprotein and acetylcholinesterase as screening parameters for neural tube defects.`,
