    correctAnswer: "C",
    explanation: `Perinatal HIV transmission rates have been reduced by more than 70% through: (1) Treatment of the mother and baby with antiretroviral treatment (ART); (2) Elective caesarean section; (3) Not breastfeeding. The Pediatric AIDS Clinical Trial Group (PACTG 076) study showed that administration of zidovudine alone, or in combination with other retroviral drugs, to HIV-infected women and their newborns reduces the risk of perinatal transmission by approximately two-thirds (from 25.5% to 8.3%). When antiretroviral therapy is combined with elective caesarean section, the risk of vertical transmission falls to 2% or less. Rates of transmission are increased in cases of: advanced maternal illness, high maternal viral load, poor maternal immune status (low CD4 count), rupture of membranes >4 hours before birth, preterm labor, vaginal delivery, and procedures that may jeopardize the integrity of natural barriers. Caesarean section alone (option A) or zidovudine alone (option B) are less effective than the combination. Combined triple antiviral therapy for the neonate (option D) is not the primary prevention strategy. Early induction of delivery (option E) is not recommended.`,
