    explanation: `Trauma is a major contributor to maternal mortality and is the leading cause of pregnancy-associated maternal deaths. Maternal trauma can compromise the fetus as a result of maternal hypotension or hypoxemia, placental abruption, uterine rupture, or fetal trauma. With bruises over the abdomen (seatbelt marks), this woman has positioned the seat belt incorrectly over the uterus. The correct position of the seat belt is when the lap belt is placed on the hip below the uterus and the sash between the breasts and above the uterus. With bruises over the abdomen, this patient should be considered as having significant abdominal trauma. A minimum 24-hour period of monitoring is recommended for all pregnant women who have sustained trauma if any of the following is present: regular uterine contractions, vaginal bleeding, a non-reassuring fetal heart rate tracing, abdominal/uterine pain, or significant trauma to the abdomen. These patients should not be discharged until the clinician reasonably makes sure that they do not have an abruption or preterm labor.`,
