    correctAnswer: "C",
    explanation: `Sodium valproate carries the highest teratogenicity rate among all antiepileptic drugs. The potential congenital defects caused by sodium valproate include: Neural tube defects (spina bifida, anencephaly); Heart defects (congenital ventricular septal defect, aortic stenosis, patent ductus arteriosus, aberrant pulmonary artery); Limb defects (radial ray defect, polydactyly, oligodactyly, absent fingers, overlapping toes, camptodactyly, split hand, ulnar or tibial hypoplasia); Genitourinary defects (hypospadias, renal hypoplasia, hydronephrosis, duplication of the calyceal system); Brain anomalies (hydranencephaly, porencephaly, arachnoid cysts, cerebral atrophy, partial agenesis of the corpus callosum, agenesis of septum pellucidum, lissencephaly, Dandy-Walker anomaly); Eye anomalies (bilateral congenital cataract, optic nerve hypoplasia, tear duct anomalies, microphthalmia, bilateral iris defects, corneal opacities); Respiratory tract defects (tracheomalacia, lung hypoplasia, severe laryngeal hypoplasia, abnormal lobulation of the right lung, right oligemic lung); Abdominal wall defects (omphalocele); Skin abnormalities (capillary hemangioma, aplasia cutis congenital of the scalp). Previously, women with epilepsy were informed that their risk for fetal malformations was increased 2- to 3-fold, but more recent data suggest that the risk may not be as great as once thought, particularly for newer agents. More recent studies showed that the risk of fetal malformation following intrauterine exposure to anticonvulsants that are currently in use is approximately the same or only slightly elevated compared to children without exposure. Nonetheless, sodium valproate is a distinct exception in antiepileptic medications.`,
