    correctAnswer: "E",
    explanation: `The triple marker screen test is done from 15 to 18 (up to 20) weeks of gestation. Since the reference values are gestational age-specific, accurate dating is important. The triple marker test includes: 1) Maternal serum alpha-fetoprotein (AFP), 2) Maternal free serum beta hCG, and 3) Maternal serum unconjugated estriol. AFP is the major serum glycoprotein of the embryo. AFP concentration peaks at 12 weeks in the fetus, and the amniotic fluid then rises in the maternal serum until 30 weeks. Fetal structural defects such as a neural tube or ventral wall defects cause spillage of more AFP into the amniotic fluid and maternal blood. Other causes of increased AFP include multiple pregnancies, placental bleeding, fetal renal disease, and sacrococcygeal teratoma. Maternal serum AFP (MS-AFP) is reported in 'multiples of median' (MoM). The most common cause of increased (>2.5 MoM) or decreased (<0.85 MoM) MS-AFP on-screen test is dating errors. Therefore, the next best step, when the values are not within the normal range, would be ultrasonography for accurate dating. MS-AFP alone is only 20% sensitive in the detection of Down syndrome. With a triple marker screen, the sensitivity rises to 70% if accurate dating based on first-trimester dating sonography is performed. With Down syndrome (trisomy 21), MS-AFP and estriol are decreased, but β-hCG is increased. With Edward syndrome (trisomy 18), all three markers are decreased. By adding the fourth marker, inhibin A, to the triple marker screen, up to 75% of Down syndrome will be detected. Inhibin A is increased in Down syndrome. None of these markers, however, are predictive of Down syndrome unless they are interpreted in conjunction with accurate gestational age. This is why ultrasonography for accurate dating is an indispensable part of marker screen tests. If the test is abnormal compared to normal values of an accurately estimated gestational age, the next step would be amniocentesis for amniotic fluid AFP, acetylcholinesterase activity, and karyotyping.`,
